-> import requests
Imports the requests library
Used to send HTTP requests (API calls)
Supports: GET, POST, PUT, DELETE

-> requests.get(url)
response = requests.get("https://petstore.swagger.io/v2/store/inventory")
What it does:
Sends a GET request to the API
Fetches data from server
Returns:
A Response object

-> Response Object (response)
This is the most important part.
It contains:
data
status
headers
JSON

-> response.text
print(response.text)
Meaning:
Returns raw response as string
Useful for:
debugging
viewing HTML/XML/text
Example Output:
{"sold":10,"available":50}
Type = str

-> response.status_code
print(response.status_code)

Used for validation in testing
Meaning:
Returns HTTP status code
Common Codes:
Code	Meaning
200	OK
201	Created
400	Bad Request
401	Unauthorized
404	Not Found
500	Server Error


-> response.json()
print(response.json())
Meaning:
Converts response into Python dictionary
Only works if response is JSON
 Example Output:
{'sold': 10, 'available': 50}
 Type = dict




Difference: text vs json()
Feature	                text        	json()
Type	                string          dictionary
Use	                    raw view	     structured data
Safe for API testing	no               yes

 requests.get() → sends request
 response → stores result
 status_code → validation
 text → raw data
 json() → parsed data

